2026-04-16 12:21:11 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['cable connections between power supply and control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The power-supply indicator LED is lit, so the PSU and its polarity relative to its own cube are correct. The control-module inverted-cables indicator LED being ON indicates that the control module senses its input pair as reversed relative to the PSU outputs. A visual inspection has already confirmed that the PSU positive output is actually connected to the control-module negative input, and the PSU negative output to the control-module positive input. This miswiring fully explains: (1) the red indicator LED being ON (its LED-resistor string is designed to light when the PSU polarity is reversed at the control module), and (2) the main lamp not turning on, because the system’s intended 12V/0V rails are inverted at the control module and therefore at the lamp, so the series diode in the load module blocks current. No other component faults are required to explain the symptoms. The root cause is therefore a polarity-inverted connection between the power supply module and the control module; correcting these two cable connections should restore normal operation.'
